         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility"> ¶ Geissois sp? Saxifrageae ¶  ¶ Tambourine Mountain ¶ Qld. ¶  ¶ It is evidently a Geissois, and probably the same of which Bentham makes mention as coming in fruit from Hastings river. ¶ NSW.Bentham ...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">83.00.00p</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From Benedetto Scortechini</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RB MSS M127, Library, Royal Botanic Gardens Melbourne.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style=""/>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn0" n="1">
                  <p rend="FootnoteText"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>MS is a fragment, and has attached to it M's herbarium label inscribed by M: 'Geissois Benthami. FvM. Tweed. 1883. Scortechini', which provides the basis for the date. However, the Tweed River, which<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>marks the boundary between<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>NSW<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>and Qld, is some distance from Tambourine Mountain; the label may therefore have belonged originally to a different specimen, leaving the dating uncertain.</p>
               </note>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Geissois sp? Saxifrageae</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Tambourine Mountain<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn1" n="2">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Qld.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>It is evidently a Geissois, and probably the same of which Bentham makes mention as coming in fruit from Hastings river.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn2" n="3">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>NSW.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>Bentham (1863-78), vol 2, pp. 446: 'The genus [Geissois]<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>is from New Caledonia, where there are 3 or 4 species, but there also appears to be an Australian one, although our specimens are insufficient for defining it. A detched raceme of old capsules with the seeds fallen out, from Cloud's Creek, Hastings river,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Beckler</seg>, much resembles those from New Caledonia'.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>I gathered the racemes on the ground, and could not discover the tree they came from. The leaves which accompany the flowers are not from the tree wherefrom the racemes dropped. They may belong to Weinmannia. On the probable supposition that the capsules and leaves from the Hastings belong to the same species to which my flowers belong, there is enough material for a description of a species of Australian Geissois. I cannot have access to any description of the Caledonian species, so I cannot say whether this Geissois from Tambourine is specifically distinct from the New Caledonian ones. You certainly possess these New Caledonian Geissoises described, or in the Herbarium, and shall be able therefore to settle the point at once.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn3" n="4">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Although M described<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">G</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">eissois benthamiana</seg>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>in B65.04.10, p. 16, he<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>does not list a<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Geissois</seg>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>species in B83.03.04, treating it as a<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">W</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">e</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">inmannia</seg>.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Geissois</p>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Saxifrageae</p>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Weinmannia</p>
         </div>
